02935cam a2200385 i 20161228114742.0m     o  d        cr unu||||||||130807s2013    miu     ob    001 0 eng d  a2013025442  a9780472118984q(hbk. : alk. paper)  a9780472029495q(e-book)7 a10.3998/mpub.4464415  aMiUbengcMiU  ae------aaw-----aff-----00aUG443b.L47 201300a355.4/409372231 aLevithan, Joshua,d1976-10aRoman siege warfare /cJoshua Levithan. 1aAnn Arbor, [Michigan] :bUniversity of Michigan Press,c[2013]  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  aIncludes bibliographical references (pages 229-238) and index.  a"Roman siege warfare had its own structure and customs, and expectations both by the besieged and by the attacking army. Sieges are typically sorted by the techniques and technologies that attackers used, but the more fruitful approach offered in Roman Siege Warfare examines the way a siege follows or diverges from typical narrative and operational plotlines. Author Josh Levithan emphasizes the human elements--morale and motivation--rather than the engineering, and he recaptures the sense of a siege as an event in progress that offers numerous attitudes, methods, and outcomes. Sieges involved a concentration of violent effort in space and the practical challenge posed by a high wall: unlike field battles they were sharply defined in time, in space, and in operational terms. Chapters examine motivation and behavior during a siege and focus on examples from both the Roman Republic and the Empire: Polybius, Livy, Julius Caesar, Flavius Josephus, and Ammianus Marcellinus. Levithan examines the "gadgetary turn," during which writers began to lavish attention on artillery and wall-damaging techniques, fetishizing technology and obscuring the centrality of the assault and of human behavior. This volume speaks to classicists and historians of all stripes. All passages are translated, and references are accessible to nonspecialists. Military historians will also find much of interest in the volume, in its treatment both of Roman military conduct and of wider military practice"--cProvided by publisher.  aDescription based on information from the publisher. 0aSiege warfarezRomexHistory. 0aSiege warfarexPsychological aspects. 0aSiege warfarexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMilitary art and sciencexHistoryyTo 500. 0aRomexHistory, Military. 4aElectronic books.2 aMichigan Publishing (University of Michigan)epublisher.40zAccess to the Michigan Publishing online version:uhttps://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.4464415